Certainly! Let's break down the design of the provided image and recreate it into a Next.js React webpage. We'll start with the CSS styling.

## Step 1: CSS Styling
1. **Global Styles**:
You can place this in a global CSS file (e.g., `styles.css` or `globals.css`).

```css
body {
    font-family: 'Arial', sans-serif; /* Use Arial as the default font, or use a similar one from Google Fonts if you prefer */
    background-color: #181818; /* Dark blue color from the design */
    color: #ffffff; /* White text color */
    margin: 0;
    padding: 0;
    box-sizing: border-box;
}

button {
    cursor: pointer;
}

.container {
    display: flex;
    justify-content: center;
    align-items: center;
    height: 100vh;
}

.search-container {
    position: relative;
    width: 400px;
}

.search-bar {
    width: 100%;
    padding: 12px 24px;
    border-radius: 8px;
    border: none;
    font-size: 18px;
}

.search-button {
    position: absolute;
    right: 10px;
    top: 50%;
    transform: translateY(-50%);
    background-color: #ffc107;
    border: none;
    border-radius: 8px;
    padding: 12px 24px;
    font-size: 18px;
}

/* Additional styles for other elements can go here */
```

2. **Specific Styles**:
If you need specific components styled differently, you can place them in separate CSS modules or inline styles in React, depending on your preference.

## Step 2: Create the Next.js React Page

1. Create a new Next.js app (if you haven't already):

```bash
npx create-next-app kagi-webpage --use-npm --style=css
cd kagi-webpage
```

2. Add the above CSS styles to the global styles.

3. Create the main page component (`pages/index.js`):

```jsx
import React from 'react';
import '../styles/globals.css';

export default function Home() {
    return (
        <div className="container">
            <div className="search-container">
                <input className="search-bar" type="text" placeholder="Let's fetch..." />
                <button className="search-button">Search</button>
            </div>
            {/* Place other components or elements here as needed */}
        </div>
    );
}
```

4. If you need any custom fonts or specific components, you might want to add them separately. For custom fonts, you can use Google Fonts or another font provider.

5. Run the development server to see your page:

```bash
npm run dev
```

This will give you a basic replica of the design in the image as a Next.js React webpage. Adjustments and refinements can be made as per your requirements.
